<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Lord Goldsmith QC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">INTRODUCTION</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In giving this evidence to the Committee I draw upon my experience in the negotiations of the EU Charter.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was appointed by the Prime Minister Tony Blair to be the UK Governme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nt </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">representative to the convention drafting the Charter. I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was actively involved in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">negotiation meetings, of which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ultimately there were some </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">29 over 9 months. I was subsequently appointed as Attorney General </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> June 2001</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and remained in office until 27 June 2007.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  In that latter capacity I was further involved with matters concerning the Charter, including the conclusion of what became Protocol 30. The normal conventions relating to the confidentiality of Law Officers’ advice apply to this latter period.</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GENESIS AND PURPOSE OF THE CHARTER AND THE UK GOVERNMENT APPROACH TO IT</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The attitude of the UK Government to the Charter was that it was not to create new rights but to make clear and accessible the existing rights that we all have and in particular the limits on the power of the European Union – Brussels, if you like – to legislate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I explained the genesis of the Charter and some of the issues to which it gave rise in several articles and speeches I have given over the years.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> speech </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I gave to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">British Institute of International and Comparative Law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I discuss</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> some of the misconstructions that have plagued the Charter since its incorporation into the Treaty of Lisbon. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In an earlier </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">article in the Common Market Law Review </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I focussed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on the gestation of the Charter and its substantive content in more detail. I ta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ke the liberty of attaching these do</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cuments to this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">memorandum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span></h1><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Charter of Fundamental Rights, Speech to British Institute of International and Comparative Law, 15 January 2008</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Annex 1)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45.97pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A Charter of Rights, Freedoms and Principles, Common Market Law Review 38: 1201-1216, 2001</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Annex 2)</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ul></ul><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As I there explain the fundamental point was to provide a clear and accessible statement of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">existing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rights and therefore constraints on the power of the EU to legislate.  The reason in my view was that the EU, when created as the European Communities, had rather been economic entities. As such, it did not include the sort of constraints in the interests of protection of fundamental freedoms on the exercise of power by the Communities’ institutions that national governments are usually subject to.  The Communities were not, for example, parties to the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). It was for that reason that when the work which led to the Charter was put in train it was explicitly stated by the European Council at its meeting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at Cologne that “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the fundamental rights applicable at Union level should be consolidated in a Charter and thereby made more evident</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.” (at para</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">graph</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 44</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the Presidency Conclusions, Cologne European Council, 3 and 4 June 1999</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NOT NEW RIGHTS</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The UK was very firm in its view that we were not there to create new rights.  I believe we were successful in that regard albeit against the opposition of some other participants and observers.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The fact that these are existing rights and not new rights is reflected in a number of places in the Charter and now in Protocol 30 as follows:</span></h1><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Preamble at paragraph 5: “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Charter reaffirms…the rights as they result, in particular, from the constitutional traditions and international obligations common to the Member States…</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Preamble at paragraph 7: “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Union therefore recognises the rights, freedoms and principles set out hereafter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Art</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 51(2)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Charter does not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">extend the field of application of Union law beyond the powers of the Union or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">establish any new power or task for the Union, or modify powers and tasks</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> defined by the Treaties.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></h2><h2 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">(d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Protocol 30, Preamble para</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">graph</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 6: “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Whereas the Charter reaffirms the rights, freedoms and principles recognised in the Union and makes those rights more visible, but does not create new rights or principles</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span></h2><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As the Commission stated in its Communication COM (2000)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">559, the task for the Convention was one of “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">revelation rather than creation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (paragraph 7)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Charter imposes no additional conditions on applicant countries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">graph</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 13). It simply puts in one place the o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bligations on member states vis-a-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vis their citizens. It does not create new rights. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is also inherent in the device of the Explanations.  The Explanations have the effect in my view of tying back the apparently broadly expressed rights which are set out in the Charter itself.  Those rights which derive from the ECHR (or “correspond to”) as was said are, for example, tied back to the ECHR and to its jurisprudence.   Others are tied back to other existing rights.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For instance, the rights being relied upon in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">R v Secretary of State EWHC 3453</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are all rights that exist not because of their mention in the Charter, but because of their status through other instruments. Specifically, Article 7 of the Charter, as set out clearly in the Explanations, “corresponds” to Article 8 of the ECHR. The protection of personal data, in Article 8 of the Charter is based not only on Article 8 of the ECHR but also, amongst other sources, on Article 286 of the Treaty establishing the European Community and Directive 95/46/EC of the European Parliament, which is already binding on Member States as part of the established body of EU law. No new right has been created, and no new right is being referred t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o in this case. Instead of referring to the Charter provisions, the claimant </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">AB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">R v Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> could rather have referred to the originating provisions bearing the relevant rights. The effect would have been the same.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Explanations are of primary importance in terms of understanding the origin and scope of the righ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ts set out in the Charter. The E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">xplanations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (based on a proposal I had advanced)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are, in their own terms, “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a valuable tool of interpretation intended to clarify the provisions of the Charter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” (Explanations, preambular paragraph).  And, critically, Article 52(7) of the Charter provides that, “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">[t]</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he explanations drawn up as a way of providing guidance in the interpretation of this Charter shall be given due regard by the courts of the Union and of the Member States</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.” Given the importance of their function, I have taken the liberty of attaching the Explanations to this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">memorandum </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(see </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Explanations Relating to the Charter of Fundamental Rights </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(2007/C 303/02), Official Journal of the European Union C 303/17, 14 December 2007</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,  at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Annex 3).</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The other important juridical device we used to constrain the Charter to its proper purpose was the so-called horizontal articles to be found in Articles 51 – 54.   They define the ambit and some aspects of interpretation of the Charter.  For example, Article 51(1) identifies that the Charter does not apply to the Member States except when they are implementing Union Law.  In other words outside that field the Charter has no application domestically.  It does not therefore represent a new ECHR.  This follows from the fact that the Charter was conceived as a way of providing protections for all citizens and others within the Union on the way that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Union powers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">were exercised.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Other horizontal articles deal with other issues eg Article 51 makes it clear that powers of the Union are limited to what is contained in the Union Treaties.  Article 52(3) is intended to ensure that in so far as rights correspond to the ECHR rights they have the same meaning and scope.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I note in that context that one issue referred to in the debate which took place on 19 November 2013 in the House of Commons was whether there was a risk of confusion because of the way rights are differently expressed between the ECHR and the Charter.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I was personally concerned about that issue and argued strenuously in my role of representative for the UK Government against taking any step which could </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lead to confusion between rights in the ECHR and rights expressed in the Charter where they covered the same grounds.  My view was not universally held.  Many members of the convention wanted to bring certain rights “up to date”.  Indeed it is in any event impossible to assert that the content of the European Convention is precisely as it was when it was propagated in 1950: the Convention is a “living instrument”, and has to be interpreted in light of present day conditions so as to be practical and effective. So, for example, the change of “correspondence” in Article 8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the ECHR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to “communications” in Article 7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the Charter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, is solely, and properly to take account of “developments in technology”, as clearly set out in the Explanations. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nonetheless I believe that the combination of Article 52(3) of the Charter, the Explanations and now the later developments including Protocol 30 have the effect of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tying back those rights to the ECHR and indeed its jurisprudence.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In any event, any perceived risk of confusion is not a real risk.  We negotiated and obtained the clear statement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in Article 52(3) of the Charter that: </span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 70.9pt; text-indent:0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In so far as this Charter contains rights which correspond to rights guaranteed by the Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, the meaning and scope of those rights shall be the same as those laid down by the said Convention. This provision shall not prevent Union law providing more extensive protection.” </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The effect of this is that where rights are based on the European Convention Rights they are, notwithstanding distances of language (to the extent that those exist which is in fact minimal), the same. The provisions have to be interpreted in exactly the same way.  This includes necessarily by reference to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">jurisprudence of the European Convention on Human Rights.</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is recognised, for instance, in the ECJ decision of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Aklagaren v Hans Akerberg Fransson </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(see paragraph 44); and in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">DEB Deutsche Energiehandels und Beratungsgesellschaft mbH v Bundesrepublik Deutschland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> C-279/09  (see paragraph 35); and in the ECJ Advocate General’s opinion in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Secretary for the Home Department v ME and others,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> C-411/10 (see for example paragraphs 145-148). </span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">THE DECISION IN AB V SECRETARY OF STATE</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I note that the event which has given rise to this inquiry is the decision, and the commentary on the decision, of Mr Justice Mostyn in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Queen on the application of AB v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (case number CO/11191/2010) delivered on 7 November 2013.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The interpretation placed on his comments is illustrated by a newspaper comment in the Evening Standard for 12 November 2013 in which it was stated that:</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 70.9pt; text-indent:0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The j</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">udge said, however, that the European Court of Justice in Luxembourg has since given a judgment which means that the Charter, which contains a ‘host of new rights’ is now valid in British courts.”</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is worth setting out the paragraph in Mr Justice Mostyn’s judgment which has given rise to this comment and to other observations.  In paragraph 14 of his judgment he said as follows:</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 70.9pt; text-indent:0.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The constitutional significance of this decision [in reference to an ECJ decision I discuss below] can hardly be overstated.  The Human Rights Act 1998 incorporated into our domestic law large parts, but by no means all, of the European Convention o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Human Rights.  Some parts were deliberately missed out by Parliament.  The Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union contains, I believe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> all of those missing parts and a great deal more.  Notwithstanding the endeavours of our political representatives </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Lisbon it would seem that the much wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">harter of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ights is now part of our domestic law.  Moreover, that much wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">harter of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ights would remain part of our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">domestic law even if the Human Rights Act were repealed.”</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In making these observations and the impression they have led to, in my view the learned Judge was mistaken in a number of fundamental respects.  I believe that he misappreciated what the Charter was seeking to do and indeed what it has done.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The most important of those errors was to fail to appreciate that the Charter does not in fact create any new rights as I explain above.  All of the rights contained in it are rights which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">exist by virtue of other existing instruments</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Part of his error is that the Judge appeared to take the view that the only instrument which created fundamental rights was the European Convention on Human Rights.  That is not the case and there are a series of other obligations, starting with the Genève Convention on Refugees from 1951 and many existing European Union obligations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contained in the treaty and in legislation, directives and regulations and so forth made under it. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A further important error made by the learned Judge was not to appreciate the extent of the application of the Charter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The Charter applies to EU institutions and Member States when implementing EU law, and is not applicable in relation to entirely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> domestic legal issues (see Article </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">51 of Charter).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  It is fair to say that I suspect the UK Government believes that the decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Secretary of State for the Home Dept v ME and others </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(21 December 2011) on which Mostyn J relied may have been in error in its approach to what </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">constitutes the implementation of Union law.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These are the two most significant errors.  When these errors are corrected and the Charter and the Protocol seen in their proper context and by proper reference to the Explanations, much, if not all, of the concern should fall away.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are certain general observations I would also like to make.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The first is to recognise that this is a complicated area in which error and misunderstanding can arise.  I apologise therefore that some of what I have to say is necessarily technical and detailed.  Nonetheless, I firmly believe that with a proper appreciation of the fundamental principles and in particular of the application of the horizontal articles and of the Explanations which I refer to below, most, and I would hope all, of the potential misunderstanding falls away.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Secondly, I make no apology for the fact that the Charter does set out certain fundamental rights which citizens of the European Union should enjoy in their relations with the European institutions.  With concern expressed in some corners about the use of power by “Brussels” it is logical to welcome and not to reject limitations on those powers which protect the fundamental rights of European citizens from abuse of power by the European Union institutions.  </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is instructive that in fact the issue which gave rise to the decision in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Secretary of State for the Home Dept v ME and others </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has actually gone away.  The problem arose because of an apparent difference in interpretation of the European Convention on Human Rights and what the Charter was thought to provide. Subsequently, a decision of the Strasbourg court in fact amended the understanding of the relevant ECHR right so that no difference between the ECHR and the Charter in fact existed.</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 4.35pt 12pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">THE PROTOCOL</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the first of the articles I have referred to above</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> I explain my understanding of P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rotocol 30. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In my view the significance for the UK of Protocol 30 on the Application of the Charter to Poland and to the United Kingdom, the provisions of which are annexed to the Treaty on European Union and to the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is to reinforce the points I have been making about the limits of the Charter.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Protocol provides at Article 1(1) that it “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">does not extend the ability of the Court of Justice of the European Union, or any court or tribunal of … the UK, to find that the laws, regulations, or administrative provisions, practices or action of … the UK are inconsistent with the fundamental rights, freedoms and principles that it reaffirms</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”. Article 1(1) is intended to make clear that the Charter is not extending fundamental rights beyond those already in existence by virtue of other instruments.</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Article 1(2) is intended to underline that by making it clear that the Charter does not create justiciable rights. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">32.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Article 2 is intended to make it clear that where reference is made to national laws and practices, it is for the UK to identify what those national laws and practices are. </span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="display:inline; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">33.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I will be happy to expand upon these points in my oral evidence.</span></h1><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 35.45pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Error! No property name supplied.</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">As the papers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">referred to at Annexes 1, 2 and 3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">are published elsewhere, they are not reproduced here </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">and do not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> form part of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">formal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">written evidence to the Committee.</span></p></body></html>